Ropes & Gray

Introduction

Theres a perception that Private Equity funds are steered & operated by indistinguishable Ivy League, B-School drones, and this may be true to some extent. However, as the industry has expanded beyond the north-eastern United States into new sectors and geographies, so the skillsets and backgrounds of those they employ have changed Todays PE xxxx

We took a look at the web biographies of 3,672 partners, associates, and employees working at 15 of the top Private Equity firms around the world, and looked at where they went to school. Heres what we found.

Summary stats table

Geography

Where are these people coming from? We have broad regional data for 96.3% of records, and more granular regional data for 90.0%.

data %>% 
  select(region) %>% 
  filter(region != "") %>% 
  group_by(region) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  mutate(p = n/length(data$region)) %>%
  mutate(percent = round(p*100, 0)) %>%
  select (-n, -p)
#  Consider displaying this as a world map.

Breaking it down yet further, we see that together North America (predominantly the US) and Europe account for around three-quarters of those for whom we have location data (based on their office.)

data %>% 
  select(region2) %>% 
  filter(region2 != "") %>% 
  group_by(region2) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  mutate(p = n/length(data$region)) %>%
  mutate(percent = round(p*100, 1)) %>%
  select (-n, -p, region = region2)
#  Consider displaying this as a world map.

University Groups

count_specific_schools_by_region <- function(s){
  data %>%
  select(region2, school) %>%
  filter(str_detect(school, paste(s, collapse = "|"))) %>%
  group_by(school, region2) %>%
  tally() %>%
  spread(region2, n) -> 
  selected_schools
 selected_schools[order(rowSums(-selected_schools, na.rm = TRUE)), 
                  order(colSums(-selected_schools, na.rm = TRUE))] %>%
   select(school, everything())
}

Gender data

While we werent able to collect explicit gender metadata, in most cases we can generate it based on gender pronouns used in the company bio. Its not a foolproof method, so we calculate the likelihood of each gender independently (well remove dubious entries later.)

read.csv("~/Documents/Private Equity Data Harvest/collated_PE_bios.tsv", sep = "\t") %>%
  select(File, name, title, location, bio) %>%
  mutate(company = gsub("_.*$", "", File)) %>%
  select(-File) %>%
  mutate(male = str_detect(bio, "\\W(H|h)(e|is)\\W"), 
         female = str_detect(bio, "\\W((S|s)he)\\W|\\W(H|h)er\\W")) %>%
  select(name, male, female, title, company) -> 
  genders
genders

Merge the genders and data tables

We could use this to cut school data by gender

left_join(data, genders, by=c("name", "company"))

Alternatively, cut gender data by location this feels more promising

right_join(genders, data, by=c("name", "company")) %>%
  mutate(query = male == female) %>%
  filter(query == FALSE, nchar(as.character(title)) != 0) %>%
  mutate(gender = case_when(male == TRUE ~ "male",
                            female == TRUE ~ "female")) %>%
  select(name, gender, title, company, region, region2)

Title Patterns

Weve created some sensible (to us) pattern groupings of job seniority, although these will need external validation.

title_patterns <- c("(?<!senior )(?<!executive )(?<!sr\\. )(?<!vice ) president",  # president
                    "partner",
                    "(?<=executive )vice president",  # EVP
                    "(?<=senior )vice president",  # SVP
                    "(?<!senior )(?<!executive )(?<!sr\\. )vice president", # VP
                    "managing director",  # managing director     
                    "(?<!managing )director",  # director
                    "principal",
                    "member",
                    "associate",
                    "marketing|communications|public(?! value)",
                    "human (resources|capital)")

Lets use these to estimate seniority by gender

genders %>%
  mutate(query = male == female) %>%
  filter(query == FALSE, nchar(as.character(title)) != 0) %>%
  mutate(gender = case_when(male == TRUE ~ "male",
                            female == TRUE ~ "female")) %>%
  select(name, gender, title) %>%
  mutate(title1=gsub("( of| and|\\,| \\&|\\|| \\-).*","",title)) %>%
  select(gender, title = title1) %>%
  group_by(gender, title) %>%
  tally() %>%
  arrange(desc(n))

Title patterns

search_titles <- function(x, pattern){
  x[str_detect(str_to_lower(x$title), pattern),]
}
genders %>%
  mutate(query = male == female) %>%
  filter(query == FALSE, nchar(as.character(title)) != 0) %>%
  mutate(gender = case_when(male == TRUE ~ "male",
                            female == TRUE ~ "female")) %>%
  select(gender, title) ->
  gender_titles

# This is fabulously ugly, but seems to work. Needs refactoring for tidyverse
count_titles <- function(df){
  datalist = list()
  for (i in seq_along(title_patterns)) {
    temp_df = search_titles(df, title_patterns[i])
    d <- data.frame(title_pattern = title_patterns[i], count = length(temp_df$title))
    datalist[[i]] <- d
  }
  
bind_rows(datalist)
}
gender_titles %>%
  filter(gender == "male") %>%
  count_titles()
gender_titles %>%
  filter(gender == "female") %>%
  count_titles()
